commits.message:
Improve logging and async handling in ResourceServer

ResourceServer now defaults to using TraceLogger if no logger is provided and properly awaits FetchBlobConfig. FetchBlobConfig is refactored to return a Task and handle missing configuration more gracefully. TraceLogger now writes logs to a file named after its namespace and sets up a TextWriterTraceListener for persistent logging.

Refactor HTTP client usage in ResourceServer

Replaced local HttpClient instantiation with the class-level _httpClient for sending requests. This improves resource management and consistency in HTTP operations.

Fix async context handling in blob config loading

Added ConfigureAwait(false) to async HTTP call and moved Compile() invocation to immediately after deserialization. This improves async context handling and ensures blob config is compiled before assignment.

Improve error handling for FetchBlobConfig

Replaces fire-and-forget async call to FetchBlobConfig with a safe pattern that logs errors if the task fails. This ensures exceptions are not silently ignored and improves reliability.

issue.body:
Hi Lee,

I implemented the ci.yml workflow with dummy NEXT_PUBLIC_CONVEX_URL for now. 

**Here are the sample run of GHA.**

https://github.com/parimalpate123/liminal-chat/actions

**Need your help on this setup in https://github.com/leegmoore/liminal-chat**

### Required GitHub Environment config (staging and production)

Add these to each environment in GitHub:
- Environment: staging
- Environment: production

Secrets (sensitive)
- CONVEX_DEPLOY_KEY: Convex deploy key for that environment
- VERCEL_TOKEN: Vercel access token
- VERCEL_ORG_ID: Vercel org ID
- VERCEL_PROJECT_ID: Vercel project ID for `apps/web`

Variables (non-sensitive)
- CONVEX_DEPLOYMENT: Convex deployment slug (e.g., modest-squirrel-498)
- NEXT_PUBLIC_CONVEX_URL: Public Convex URL for that environment (from Convex dashboard)

Notes
- CI uses the staging environment. Ensure `staging` has `NEXT_PUBLIC_CONVEX_URL` set or Next.js build will fail.
- CD reads all values from the selected environment when you run `cd.yml`.

Where to get values
- CONVEX_DEPLOY_KEY, CONVEX_DEPLOYMENT, NEXT_PUBLIC_CONVEX_URL:
  - Convex dashboard ‚Üí your project ‚Üí deployment settings (URL and slug shown there; deploy key under Settings/Keys)
- VERCEL_TOKEN:
  - Vercel account settings ‚Üí Tokens
- VERCEL_ORG_ID, VERCEL_PROJECT_ID:
  - Vercel ‚Üí Project ‚Üí Settings ‚Üí General (IDs)
  - Or via CLI: `vercel link` will print them

How to add them (per environment)
- GitHub ‚Üí Settings ‚Üí Environments ‚Üí New environment ‚Üí ‚Äústaging‚Äù
- Open ‚Äústaging‚Äù ‚Üí Add secret ‚Üí name and value (repeat for each secret)
- Add variable ‚Üí name and value (repeat for each variable)
- Repeat for ‚Äúproduction‚Äù with production values

Optional (only if you enable post‚Äëdeploy tests later)
- Secrets for local JWT minting and provider APIs:
  - SYSTEM_USER_EMAIL, SYSTEM_USER_PASSWORD, WORKOS_CLIENT_ID, WORKOS_API_KEY
  - OPENAI_API_KEY, ANTHROPIC_API_KEY, GOOGLE_GENERATIVE_AI_API_KEY, OPENROUTER_API_KEY, PERPLEXITY_API_KEY, VERCEL_API_TOKEN
- Typically set these in Convex dashboard for runtime; only add to GitHub if you plan to manage them from CI.

pull_request.body:
Thanks for asking me to work on this. I will get started on it and keep this PR's description up to date as I form a plan and make progress.

Original description:

> # Copilot Agent PR Task Prompt
> 
> ## Title
> 
> Finish `ctx`‚Üí`runtime` migration in run‚Äëprep; add guardrails to prevent bare `ctx` reintroduction
> 
> ## Repository Context
> 
> * Python 3.12 trading bot on systemd.
> * Risk engine and strategy loading is green.
> * `runtime.params` is present and logged (`PARA‚Ä¶TIVE`).
> * Current error: `NameError: name 'ctx' is not defined` at `_prepare_run` assigning `ctx.tickers = symbols`.
> 
> ## Problem Statement
> 
> A final bare `ctx` reference remains in `_prepare_run` (and possibly nearby helpers). We must:
> 
> 1. write tickers (and any other per‚Äëcycle fields) to the **canonical runtime object**, not a free `ctx`;
> 2. ensure the `BotRuntime` schema exposes these fields; and
> 3. add a simple static check to prevent bare `ctx` usage from creeping back in hot paths.
> 
> ## Scope of Work
> 
> 1. Replace `ctx.tickers = symbols` with `runtime.tickers = symbols` in `_prepare_run`.
> 2. Ensure `BotRuntime` defines `tickers: list[str]` (and any other fields `_prepare_run` sets) with safe defaults.
> 3. Repo‚Äëwide sweep in production modules for any remaining bare `ctx` reads/writes and replace with `runtime`.
> 4. Add a lightweight CI/static guard that fails the build if `ctx` is used in `ai_trading/core/bot_engine.py` or `ai_trading/risk/*` outside of a local variable parameter name.
> 
> ## Acceptance Criteria
> 
> * No more `NameError: ctx` in any startup or loop logs.
> * `_prepare_run` successfully sets `runtime.tickers` and proceeds.
> * `python -m py_compile $(git ls-files '*.py')` passes.
> * A CI/static check ensures no bare `ctx` usage remains in hot paths.
> 
> ## Change Details
> 
> ### 1) BotRuntime schema
> 
> **File:** `ai_trading/core/runtime.py` (or wherever `BotRuntime` lives)
> 
> ```python
> from dataclasses import dataclass, field
> from typing import List, Optional
> 
> @dataclass
> class BotRuntime:
>     cfg: "TradingConfig"
>     params: dict = field(default_factory=dict)
>     tickers: List[str] = field(default_factory=list)  # <-- add
>     # consider adding: account, positions, broker, clocks, etc., if not already present
> ```
> 
> *(No behavior change; just ensures the attribute exists.)*
> 
> ### 2) Replace the offending write in run‚Äëprep
> 
> **File:** `ai_trading/core/bot_engine.py`
> 
> * Around the line indicated in logs (`_prepare_run`, \~9371):
> 
> ```python
> # OLD
> ctx.tickers = symbols
> 
> # NEW
> runtime.tickers = symbols
> ```
> 
> * Double‚Äëcheck the surrounding function: ensure **every** call uses `runtime` (not `ctx`) and that any helpers it calls accept `runtime` explicitly.
> 
> ### 3) Repo‚Äëwide sweep for bare `ctx` in prod
> 
> * Replace lingering occurrences in prod modules:
> 
>   * `ai_trading/core/bot_engine.py`
>   * `ai_trading/risk/*`
>   * any other `ai_trading/*` code paths touched during the ctx‚Üíruntime migration
> 
> Guideline:
> 
> * Function signatures: `def foo(runtime, ...)`
> * No free/global `ctx` references; if you need a shorter alias inside a function, assign `ctx = runtime` **as a local** and never rely on a global binding.
> 
> ### 4) Static guard (simple and effective)
> 
> **File:** `scripts/check_no_ctx.py` (new, optional but recommended)
> 
> ```python
> import sys, re, pathlib
> 
> PATTERN = re.compile(r"\bctx\b")
> ALLOW = re.compile(r"def\s+\w+\(.*\bctx\b")  # allow as a parameter name only if you insist
> 
> failures = []
> roots = ["ai_trading/core/bot_engine.py", "ai_trading/risk"]
> for root in roots:
>     p = pathlib.Path(root)
>     files = [p] if p.is_file() else p.rglob("*.py")
>     for f in files:
>         text = f.read_text(encoding="utf-8", errors="ignore")
>         for m in PATTERN.finditer(text):
>             # ignore matches where used as part of a longer name (_ctx is fine),
>             # and optionally allow parameter names if you keep them:
>             start = max(0, m.start()-20)
>             snippet = text[start:m.start()+20]
>             if re.search(r"\b_ctx\b", snippet):  # ignore _ctx
>                 continue
>             if ALLOW.search(snippet):  # optional relaxation
>                 continue
>             failures.append(str(f))
>             break
> 
> if failures:
>     print("Bare 'ctx' usage detected in:", *failures, sep="\n- ")
>     sys.exit(1)
> print("OK")
> ```
> 
> Add to CI or pre‚Äëcommit; or just run locally:
> 
> ```
> python scripts/check_no_ctx.py
> ```
> 
> ## Constraints & Standards
> 
> * No shims; no `scripts/*` in prod paths.
> * Do not add `except Exception:`; keep exceptions scoped.
> * Keep existing structured logging and secret masking.
> 
> ## Validation Steps
> 
> 1. `python -m py_compile $(git ls-files '*.py')`
> 2. `python scripts/check_no_ctx.py` ‚Üí `OK`
> 3. Restart service and observe:
> 
>    * Startup INFO lines,
>    * Single ‚Äútickers.csv‚Äù warning (not duplicated),
>    * Screener logs,
>    * **No** `NameError: ctx`,
>    * Heartbeats continue; loop does not crash.
> 
> ## Risk & Rollback
> 
> * **Risk:** Low; it‚Äôs a one‚Äëliner functional change plus schema declaration.
> * **Rollback:** Revert this PR to previous state (where the loop crashes).
> 
> ---
